BepiColombo, a joint ESA-Japanese Space Agency Mission (JAXA) flew past the planet Venus on Tuesday, August 10 at 552 kilometers (340 miles) away. It took its pictures as it moved past Venus, showing the planet receding further and further from view. The probe will be able to continue its photographing and taking measurements until August 18. This footage here is made from 89 images taken by the spacecraft and stitched together by the team. 

Credit: ESA/BepiColombo/MTM

Happy #MicrobeMonday! Today we’re bringing you a wonderful little tardigrade. We’ve posted about these little water bears many times in the past, but did you know they have four to six claws on each foot to help them cling to plant matter? They also have a needle-like mouth part that can extend and pierce plant cells to drink up its delicious cytoplasm. Yum!
​ 
Video courtesy of @jam_and_germs

node.text:
The BMC Ecology and Evolution Image Competition winners have been announced, with this stunning photograph depicting a school of jack fish in a spiral formation taken by Kristen Brown from the University of Pennsylvania being crowned the overall winner.

Kristen Brown said: “This image represents both the beauty and bounty of our oceans as well as the spiralling crisis unfolding within the marine environment.”

The photo competition was created by the Springer Nature journal and BMC to give ecologists and evolutionary biologists the opportunity to use their creativity to highlight their work and celebrate the intersection between art and science.
​ 
Image Credit: Kristen Brown

node.text:
Here kitty kitty! The Bengal cat is a mix of domestic cats, particularly the spotted Egyptian Mau, and the Asian leopard cat. Their golden sheen derives from their leopard cat ancestors, which have spots and arrowhead patterns on their fur.

As wild as their appearance sounds, their personality greatly reflects that, with the Bengal cat being a naturally energetic breed that needs their play and exercise. They can also naturally retrieve items and enjoy playing in water, as seen here with this kitty playing by the seashore. Aww!

Image credit: Jevgenija ZUK / Shutterstock

Introducing IFLScience Alphabet Facts! Be on the lookout for a new word design every few weeks, as we bring you the wonderful, wacky world of science - one letter at a time! The first is A for Alien.

Did you know that earlier this year, the CIA released their UFO files to the public? You can now download pretty much everything the CIA has on record about extraterrestrials. As it turns out, there’s quite a lot... 

Every file that the CIA has declassified so far can be accessed via The Black Vault. The organization has been working to get the files released since 1996, and finally has them all there and ready to peruse in handy, searchable PDF format.

Hit this image post via the link in our bio to learn more.

Artwork by @jamescreatesletters

A blood-red, never-before-seen species of jellyfish has been spotted off the coast of Newport, Rhode Island. During an ambitious deep-ocean expedition, researchers from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) discovered the crimson creature minding its own business almost 700 meters (2,300 feet) below sea level.​
​
Video courtesy of NOAA

node.text:
This slime mold is on its way to the ISS!

Slime molds are peculiar single-cell organisms – not animal, plant or fungus. This particular one, Physarum polycephalum, is nicknamed the “Blob”. It has 720 sexes and despite not having a brain can move, feed, and organize itself. It can even transmit knowledge to other slime molds. Scientists at the European Space Agency are curious how it will act and behave in microgravity. If you think this sounds like the start of a disaster/horror movie, you are not alone.

Happy #WorldLizardDay! This may look like a dragon, but it's actually a red-eyed crocodile skink. Tribolonotus gracilis' live in the tropical rainforests of New Guinea island in Indonesia and Papua New Guinea. These sneaky lizards are known to play dead when startled to avoid harm and deter predators, and they're known as crocodile skinks due to their dorsal scales, which resemble those of a crocodile.
​
Video courtesy of @romanne_c

BepiColombo grabs a startling photo of Venus during a recent flyby.

BepiColombo (the best-named space mission) is on its way to Mercury. To get there it needs a little help. It’s using the gravity of planets like Earth and Venus to slingshot its way into the inner Solar System. This “gravity assist maneuver” also known as a “flyby” was invented by Italian scientist Guiseppe Colombo, who calculated we could get to Mercury via Venus. 

BepiCololmbo took this photo of Venus on August 10 just after its closest approach of 552 kilometers away. It’s completed three of its nine flybys on its 7-year journey to Mercury. Its next is actually at Mercury in October this year, where it will use Mercury to brake against the Sun’s gravity and swing into the orbit of its new home.
